NEW += '                    <div class="warn-box" style="line-height:1.75">\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 1] Not using f(R) &minus; f(L&minus;1) and encoding both bounds in one DP:</strong> Beginners build a two-tight-flag DP when f(R) &minus; f(L&minus;1) suffices. Correct model for 95% of problems: define f(x); answer = f(R) &minus; f(L&minus;1). Only use two tight flags when bounds are given as strings or must be processed simultaneously.<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 2] Confusing "digit sum mod K" with "value mod K":</strong> Recurrences differ completely. Digit sum: next = (current + d) % K &mdash; linear. Number value: next = (current &times; 10 + d) % K &mdash; polynomial. Mixing gives wrong answers silently.<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 2] Omitting leading_zero flag when constraint involves digit 0:</strong> Without the flag, "007" contributes two 0s to digit count or sets bit 0 in bitmask. Any constraint involving digit 0 requires leading_zero; include by default.<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 3] Building state tuple without verifying state space fits memory:</strong> 18 &times; 2 &times; 2 &times; 10&#8310; = 72M entries &times; 8 bytes = 576 MB. Before coding, multiply all dimensions. If &gt; 10&#8311;, seek compression (LCM, meet-in-middle, smarter encoding).<br>\n'
NEW += '                        &bull; <strong>[Stage 4] Missing digit DP applicability for string-counting problems:</strong> Strings over lexicographic range [s1, s2] with char-level constraints ARE digit DP. "Digits" = characters; "tight" = lexicographic; upper bound = s2. Substitution is lossless.<br>\n'
